<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO ART VARANELLI</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec 18 18:16:25 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Arthur, I agree wholeheartedly that there exists an in-depth body of knowledge about all our history.  It is lodged in the actual papers and photographs and other physical records stored in the libraries and hearts of the country.  However, my point was that the emphasis placed on the facts contained in all those records will be to focus on the particular viewpoint of the person or persons writing the history or teaching the course.  That is not a condemnation of the actual history or the physical records, it is just a statement of how the world works.  It isn't even maliciousness on the part of the persons writing or teaching, it is human nature.  Texans remember the Alamo one way, Mexican Nationals remember it another.  It will be the same with Viet Nam, especially after those with first hand knowledge and experience both pro and con have passed from the scene.  There may very well be a number of people or organizations that will retain an interest 100 years from now, but go out on the street and ask the first 100 people you come across to name 10 major engagements in the Civil War, WWI, WWII, or Viet Nam.  You know as well as I what the result will likely be.<br><br>
Finally, I'm not pessimistic about the process represented by this web site or by the on-going dialogs that I have read.  I think that healing will take place.  I think that positive attitudes will be engendered that may well result in the establishment of an atmosphere where such as Viet Nam can not again happen.  But I firmly believe that the 'history' written and taught will have personal, and perhaps even official, bias attached.  How can it be otherwise?<br><br>
Sincerely
